<!-- Promise and Its States in JavaScript

A Promise is an object that represents the eventual result of an asynchronous 
operation. It acts as a placeholder for a value that may be available now, later,
 or never. Promises are used to handle asynchronous tasks such as API requests, file operations, and database queries.
 
A Promise can exist in three states:

Pending – The initial state. The asynchronous operation is still in progress, 
and the result is not yet available.
Fulfilled (Resolved) – The operation has completed successfully, and the 
Promise returns a value.
Rejected – The operation has failed, and the Promise returns an error or 
reason for failure. -->

<!-- Example:

const promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    let success = true;

    if (success) {
        resolve("Operation Successful");
    } else {
        reject("Operation Failed");
    }
});

In this example, the Promise starts in the Pending state. If success is true,
it becomes Fulfilled and returns "Operation Successful". If success is false, 
it becomes Rejected and returns an error message. -->